< Review>
I brought my car in yesterday, 11/25, to change out my rear driver side tire that had a large screw lodged in one of the treads. When I discovered it, I put duct tape over the screw to keep it in place and let me drive to an auto shop. I had visited another auto shop first who indicated they couldn't repair the tire due to weakening of the sidewall. I placed an order for new tires that would arrive on 11/27. However, I was planning to drive to LA for Thanksgiving and didn't want to do so with a weakened tire and decided to just replace the one tire. I explained this at Big O as the reason for wanting to only replace one tire as opposed to all 4 as is normally done. The service was done, then I departed for Los Angeles today.

100 miles in to the journey, my check engine light comes back on. I was surprised because I had my car serviced on 11/24 at the dealer. I also had just replaced my first flat tire after 50k miles and figured it was unlikely to have another literally the next day. I stopped and saw that my front driver side tire was low on pressure. I began inspecting the treads and found the very same screw as before that had duct tape over it. The one individual tire I paid to be specifically replaced was simply put back on to my car and one of my good tires was disposed of. The duct tape held up long enough that I didn't realize any of this until many miles away.

I realize this exact situation may not happen to many people, but nevertheless it's frustrating and worrying as I question driving another 300 miles with a faulty tire and paying another shop to fix this.</Review>

<Time>1522564214583< /Time>< Review>
So,  the mechanics are super nice and they do quality work.  Good pricing. The waits usually a couple hours.  This is my second time visiting here. I knocked a star because at some point during my tire rotation and oil change,  the works opened my glove compartment,  probably to look for registration,  and , in their apparently mad scramble, the knocked out out a bunch of the other stuff I had in there. Wouldn't have cared or probably even noticed if they had just put it back,  but for some reason they just left it.
So I picked up my car after it was serviced, thanked the dude who gave me back my keys, and got in. Low and behold, the passenger side is strewn with the shame of my glove compartment hoarding--- manicure kit,  napkins,  old mail,  my emergency m&ms. Granted,  they couldn't have anticipated the open, half empty bag of candy would be in the compartment,  but I was honestly thrown by the fact that they just left all the mess on my floor for me to see. Just weird. Those wasted m&ms just taunted me from my passenger seat.   Anyways,  I'll probably go back again,  and just leave the registration on the seat for them.

Tl;Dr:  good prices,  good service, service might take a while.  Leave your registration/manual in an easy to reach place for the workers.</Review>

I received an original quote for four new tires online.  When I called in advance of my appointment, I was told those tires were not in stock, which I found strange, since the appointment to install them had been confirmed.  Nevertheless, I was offered a better, more expensive tire, at the same price.  I was skeptical at first -- I always think I'm getting ripped off -- but researched the tires and found the ones offered, were, in fact, substantially better.  So, that was fantastic.

I was also told on my call that it would take about 90 minutes to install my tires.  I planned my morning around that.  When I arrived -- 10 minutes before my appointment time -- I was told it would be 2-3 hours.  In fact, it took 3 hours, plus another hour to do a recommended alignment.  That was not so fantastic.

When I came to pick up the car, I asked to see the alignment report.  I remarked that only one of the measurements was out of spec and asked if that was enough to warrant an alignment.  The guy behind the counter gave me a look like I was a total idiot and quickly brushed off my question in a way that made me feel like a total idiot.  Fact is, I am a total idiot when it comes to cars.  That's why I always feel like I'm getting ripped off.  But, I don't want to be made to feel that way.  A better approach might be for the person to walk me through how to properly read the alignment report and explain what the measurements actually mean, in addition to their implications for safety, comfort, tire wear, etc.-- things I was later able to go home and research on the internet.

Prior to that experience at pick-up, everyone had been friendly, professional and courteous.  Big O is a fine place to get your tires done.< /Text>

Good caregivers are not being paid enough or being given enough hours to make the transportation time, if on the bus, around the city sustainable. Travel time should be compensated. Cambrian is not accountable to us, as the recipient, or to the caregiver. They read the notes they have taken regarding our account to the caregiver. Do not expect privacy laws to followed by the staff at Cambrian. Largely. Cambrian fails in their duties of communicating to either recipient or caregiver. Misundetstandings happened alot because of this and Cambrian always blamed someone else for any misunderstanding.Overall, at the most vulnerable time when you need real caregivers Cambrian provides questionable service. <user>100530674404249742100</user><Date>1513288202063<//Date><Pics>None</Pics><Rate>5</Rate>< gmap_id>
0x80dd31c1241711d7:0x2898cdcdab2b6ad5<//gmap_id>
<Name>Abyss Vendetta< /Name>< review>
Hiring a caregiver 101. Due diligence! Caregivers are givers of care, not dealers of cash. The bare bones salary is below living wages for most people. Consider our pay a supplement to care for the family we have to support as well. That said KNOW YOUR NEEDS! Do you tell the agency exactly what you want from  your special needs caregiver?
Here's my list.
Speak English.
Safty first CPR First aid certification
Self starter
Critical thinker
Transporter
Medical assistance
Energetic
Light to medium housework EVERY TIME
No cell phone compulsives please
Kind and patient
Reliable
Do you think that for $10.50 an hour you will find all that? I'm going to say "meh" but you have a chance of finding it at Cambrian. My experience with the company has been extremely positive. If your looking for a permanent solution,  check everywhere.  Even Craig's list. Caregivers are primarily independent contractors. We enjoy flexibility, the ability to pick and choose. While you evaluate us we are evaluating you. Does your house look like an episode of Horders?!? Does it wreak of dirty diaper and rotton food? Do you provide such little support for the caregiver as to insist all parties involved are to remain trapped inside the filthy mess of your life the entire length of stay. Not even fresh air or clean surroundings?
Seriously? Many families are in a huge amount of need. I get it, my mom is 82 and I care for her as well. Cambrian respite is wonderful if you know how to manage them. Make a list, check it twice. The State pays for most of our salary, (imagine a more cold and distant employer.) The staff at Cambrian works hard to find a good fit for  your needs. As far as my experience they will not stop until you are taken care of. We have work ethic and are proud of our work. It is the commitment to care that is shared up the chain of command.
So before you judge take a deep breath, is the plank in your eye so large you can not see the sliver in your Caregivers? Yes, some of us even have morals, standards and ethics that are at least as high as yours.  Like your loved one, we have feelings too. Most of us love what we do, it is our essence. Please try not to stamp out our fire. We're the ones who will be wiping your bottoms. Cambrian is quality care, excellent service and most are professional. I am also a CNA with vast experience in Geriactric and Devopmental special needs care. I work with all types of tramatic brain Injury. Gourmet cook,life skills coach etc. Good luck and don't forget to include Cambrian on your search for the perfect caregiver. BTW be prepared because someone with the qualifying experience you want usually starts at $15.00 to  $20.00 an hour thought a private source and more for an agency.<//review>

<user_name>Eilo Betoushana<//user_name><date>1567224555898</date><Rate>5<//Rate><review>I'm now on keto, I live in Tracy and it looks like I'll be making frequent trips to Betty's in the near future. Earlier today I told my wife that I was craving Kabobs and I really wanted to feast but didn't want to spend a bunch of money at a sit down nor did I want to fire up the grill and go through that hassle of making kabobs. A couple weeks back we passed Betty's after church but I was in a rush to get home but the smell of the Kabobs were stuck in my head since then. I called them up today and a lovely lady picked up the phone and I ordered 2 koobideh dinner plates, a skewer of tomatos, 5 skewers of koobideh and 1 skewer of chicken breasts. Let me tell you they like to add roasted jalapenos on the side for free which was an awesome bonus. All of this for less than $60!!!!! I gave them $60 and an extra $10 as tip. This much food would be well over $100 anywhere else. The owners were extremely hospitable and accommodating. I told them I would be cutting it close to their closing time and they said no worries and they waited for me. I don't think I'll ever make Kabobs at home anymore. I'll be using Betty's from now on for all my events. This is a must go to for Keto meats.< /review>< pictures>

Not your average burger joint.  Walk in and... Opa!  It is actually a Mediterranean restaurant!  Authentic Mediterranean dishes along side great burger options. <name>LeAnn Foss<//name><date>1510173379789< /date><GmapID>0x80c2c1510b446465:0xc474c796b47d40db<//GmapID><pictures>[{'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipMtHbs4uFWlt8TH4WeDRxCrSRMDn2ln7GL5rJM=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipPPLN7ncT1JbWqT_Qxtk3_ReyHEY8hNmIGf4bs=w150-h150-k-no-p']}]</pictures>< text>
Got my first tattoo here! I was looking for months for an artist who does watercolor tattoos well in the Los Angeles area and was about to give up and book a flight to another country when I came across June's work on Instagram. I went to a tattoo convention where there were hundreds of artists to see who else was available in the LA area. Seeing June's unique style juxtaposed with all the other artists there, I knew she was just what I was looking for!

June and Rob were super helpful and personable throughout the consultation/design process and responded quickly via email to all of my questions and requests. I gave June my concept for the design, and she took off and ran with it.

The day of the actual appointment, I was running late and didn't have time to eat beforehand. Without skipping a beat, Rob offered me and my friend that I had brought with me a selection of healthy snacks they had on hand. June and Rob did a great job of putting me at ease, knowing that I was nervous because it was my first tattoo. Also, a note about the space.... most tattoo shops are cluttered and kitschy. This place is not that. It's super open and you feel like you can actually breathe. Waaaayyyyy less stressful for someone like me who was nervous to begin with!

Here comes the best part.... the whole tattoo only took 2 hours! I've gotten a million compliments on it, and everyone is always blown away by how detailed it is. Most people assume that it took several sessions and hardly believe me when I tell them it only took 2 hours!

Tl;dr June is great.<//text>

<name>Wayne S.</name><time>1573536388950</time><Rating>5< /Rating>< review>
Lemon Shark Poke,located in the beautiful foothills community of Yucaipa California,
serves the freshest poke style cuisine around!
The restaurant is sparkling clean, big windows,has loads of seating inside and out and plenty of free parking!
The servers are courteous and helpful-they have a wide selection of poke choices,sauces,appetizers-I had the spam nori wrapped rice with drizzle sauce-really great!
All the signature poke bowls are great-portions are generous too!
They have "Stubborn" craft beverages on draft in all the favorite soda flavors too.
A really terrific highly recommended poke experience for lunch,dinner or snack!
.
.
.
.
.

< review>
Five stars all around! This place is amazing! My wife and I booked our spots for Valentine‚Äôs Day and it was the best date we‚Äôve had in a very long time. All the staff are kind, fun, polite and very helpful. The set up and vibe in the studio was really nice too. They have a bar that serves beer and wine, soda pop and water and snacks too, which is a bit over priced though (a bag of cornuts was $4.00 and a Baby Ruth candy bar was also $4.00) but the service was great. You can bring your own snacks, we saw another couple bring a plate of crackers and cheese and fruit. They provide all the art supplies as well as a canvas that you‚Äôll paint on and aprons to help you not get dirty. They play good music and have fun games in between and during the painting session, where you can win prizes. My wife and I ended up winning a really cool and neat free  painting. The instructor was awesome and fun and she has a great friendly sweet personality. She gives painting instructions on stage and she has a microphone so you‚Äôll be able to hear her instructions just fine and they have a tv screen on the wall showing you every painting step along the way so you won‚Äôt miss nothing. The staff walks around too helping you out and giving you more paint and art supplies if you need them. Having the opportunity to meet other people was fun too. You get to sit next to others as well as the company you come with. Overall the entire art studio was amazing! The experience alone was amazing and my wife and I will definitely be coming back for another date. They have classes for every occasion and group sessions and party sessions for adults. The restrooms are easily accessible and clean. Parking is convenient and easy to find too. Come early before your session so you can get settled in and get your drinks. They have silhouette paintings that you can have fun with and put your face up to and take pictures and post on social media or to just have for your memories. They take a group picture after the class which is free and they send it to you through your email that you booked the art session with, it‚Äôs neat to have as a reminder of good times. They also walk around the art studio during the session taking pictures of everyone and everything that‚Äôs going on to have for their social media and art studio. You will definitely have lots of fun at this studio and taking home your painting is really cool too. Five stars for this art studio and everything it represents. I recommend Painting with a Twist to everyone, it is definitely something you need to experience!<//review>

< Text>
The experience was fun, but unlike Painted Cabernet, your ticket to Painted with a Twist did NOT include an alcoholic beverage. The music did not fit the crowd, but luckily improved by mid-class. The instructor was good, but not as detailed and helpful as some I've had at Painted Cabernet. Overall, it was still really fun with friends and I'd go back. By looking at the walls, there is a MUCH larger painting selection at Painted with a Twist.< /Text>

< review>
First let me say, the front desk staff was very kind and friendly. I chose this place for the kitchen, and thought I was getting a real deal. Very disappointed. The place is showing serious wear and lack of long term maintenance. Hard water deposits on the sink fixture and mold stains in the bathroom indicate someone occupied this room for a long time without any basic cleaning. Frame on the bathroom mirror was worn away to bare wood. Floor was brand new laminate, I've got a good guess as to why. Only a small bit of toilet paper left on the roll and no spare, hair in the shower drain. No door sweep let in cold air all night with only one thin blanket and no spare. Door frame seemed a little out of place, and deadbolt seemed offset, as if the door was busted open at some point? Fire alarm went off at 2 am for about 30 seconds and I worried about my safety the rest of the night. I know this is supposed to be a long term option, but wouldn't expect this lack of care and maintenance in a Motel 6. Perhaps they cater to transitional housing for the homeless? Won't stay here again.</review>

< Text>
Quite possibly the worst hotel I've ever stayed in. I chose the hotel for the kitchenette but when I checked in and asked for dishes I was told that they were out of dishes. So then what did a pay for? A kitchen with no dishes? When I got to my room it was quite unpleasant inside. Housekeeping was just leaving when I arrived, yet it looked like this room hadn't been properly cleaned in months. There are stains all over the floor. Big, dark, highly-visible stains from who-knows-what. All the furniture felt sticky and grimey. There was a layer of soap scum in the tub that looked like it hadnt been cleaned in years and I found human hairs in the bed and the tub. Also, the door didnt fit in the frame properly, so there was a crack near the bottom that let in cool air and noise and light. The outside of the hotel was just as nasty as the inside. When you exit your room you are hit with a smell of refuse, garbage, cigarette smoke and reefer. So that was nice. The garbage cans on the stair wells were constantly overflowing and leaking garbage and waste for my entire stay. At the end if the first night I went back to the front desk to see if they had more dishes ready and I was told the only thing they had available was a single skillet. Just a skillet. Thats it. No other utinsels or dishes. So I wasn't able to eat a real dinnrr that night necause I used my whole budget on groceries that needed to be cooked. Using the kitchenette that I paid for you know? But all I had was a skillet. So that night I sent an email to the customer service office and told them the issue. The next day the girl at the front desk (I think her name was Whitney) gatherred some dishes for me. She seemed to be the only person here who actually cared to do her job, so thank you Whitney. Soon after the manager called me to address the email I had sent. They said they would credit me $20 for my trouble (never saw that money...) And that they would send housekeeping to do a deep cleaning on my room on Tuesday at 10:00 AM so I should put all my personal belongings in a corner so they wouldn't be in the way. I did as instructed and waited. By 11:30 I finally left to run my errends for the day. Housekeeping never came to my room for my entire 8 day stay. I had to ask Whitney for extra towels (again, thank you Whitney). After this exoerience, I will never stay with Extended Stay America again. This hotel was not worth the money I paid.<//Text>

<user>100140576941170884716<//user>< name>
Brian Buschman< /name>
<time>1447673666105< /time>< Rate>
3< /Rate>
< review>
Last month I stayed there Sunday - Friday two consecutive weeks. I was a guy traveling on business without my family. It was reasonably clean and safe. Right next to the highway and next a reasonably priced grocery store. My first week on the top floor I got a good room. My only problem was that dishes don't come in the room but you ask for them. My first morning I ask and was told they would be delivered that AM. After work I had to ask again and they gave me a pile of dishes and a coffee maker to carry up so I could make dinner.

The breakfast is pretty sparse having granola bars, apples, oranges and oatmeal packets. The problem is most mornings the oatmeal was only regular flavor with nothing but the coffee sweetners to put in it. They had light roast, dark roast and water for tea or hot chocolate. No decaf but I could make it in my room when I had a coffee maker.

The second week I was on the middle floor. Still clean but I could hear every footstep above me and the recliner was broken. As I was checking in on Nov 1st I ask why they were sold out and was told it was Welfare check day and they always fill up that day. As I was unloading my cart I had a guy walking the hotel (rooms open to outdoors) offering to sell me a $10 "new" leather jacket. I almost flashed him my badge but he moved on when I said no.

I did have trouble getting dishes again. I got most the day of check in but was told there were no coffee makes available. Not a huge deal to head back to the police academy the next day with no decaf and got it the next day when I ask.  In this room I also had toilet problems that resulted in being handed a plunger from the desk at first, a visit by mantience the next day and getting to keep the plunger the rest of the week when problems returned.

That week we also had the Internet go out around lunch and it took them about 48hrs to get it up and working. Xfinity came out on that second day. At home when I call Xfinity in the evening they have fixed it that night or in the AM at the latest. I just upped the data on my cell. Cost a few bucks but with the cheap hotel price I was still ahead.

Overall I am rating it 3 stars as it was clean, safe, close to the police academy and cheap. It's no 3, 4 or 5 star hotel experience but it's an inexpensive place to stay. If you want the 4 star hotel you can pay $125/night in that area but I paid $75 with taxes and dealt with these things. I would still go back for the cost savings.</review>

< text>
The hotel is very dirty. There are trash cans filled with garbage that doesnt appear to be emptied consistently (pregnancy tests, used condoms, etc were all seen). There were a LOT of people parked at the hotel and living in their vehicles with their pets. The rooms smell bad. We stayed in a non-smoking room and the smell (not cigarette smell) was horrible. We had to cover our nose in order to sleep. The pillows cases were wrinkled/creased as if they had just been used. There was visible stuff on the carpet that could have easily be vacuumed up. There were no towels in the bathroom and there was an open/used bar of soap sitting on the counter. I had an Expedia coupon so we only paid $30 for this $80 hotel and even then I feel that we paid too much. We checked in really late so we decided to not leave in the middle of the night but would have probably been more comfortable sleeping in our car. I do not recommend this hotel and I will not be staying at a Stay America again.</text>
